Democracy without popular solidarity
Something has happened to democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, and this is true everywhere in the world.
Somehow, people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of the European Parliament elections, the voter turnout was so low that the legitimacy of the election results is in question.
In addition to voter turnout, we have gotten used to considering parties or candidates who received 25% of the votes cast as "winners."
From Holland to Finland, and on to Argentina and Japan, majority governments are formed based on minorities.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American presidents have been elected by more than 10% of the eligible voters. In fact, half of the eligible voters in the United States have not even registered to vote; of those who have registered, half do not vote; and of those who do vote, less than half vote for the winning candidate.
Even Tony Blair's "dammbruchartige" (dams-breaking) majority in the UK House of Commons is on shaky ground: The Labour Party only received just over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, with a voter turnout of 60%.
Thus, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, the situation regarding elections is clearly different now than it was twenty, or even fifty years ago.
What happened?
One answer could be that voters distrust the political parties.
The electoral democracy functions in most countries due to the mediation of organizations that put forward candidates who advocate for specific packages of political options, for a "manifesto" or a "party program."
For a number of reasons, this long-established practice no longer works.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages offered by the parties, they want to pick and choose for themselves.
In addition, the political parties became machines composed of tightly organized cadres of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more clique-like despite the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have distanced the parties from the voters.
Because most people don't want to belong to any particular party, only a minority still plays the game of party politics.
This also increases the public's suspicion of political parties, not least because, like in professional sports, it is expensive to participate.
If the costs are borne by the taxpayer, it is taken very badly.
Yet without financial support from the state, parties would have to obtain money through channels that are often dubious, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of the past decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other evidence - such as the clear decline in memberships - confirms that the parties have become unpopular.
Nevertheless, parties are indispensable for a democratic election system.
The result is an obvious division between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Because the parties are active in the parliaments, the effects of this separation concern one of the key institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that parliaments represent them and are therefore equipped with the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, rather independent development comes into play.
People are more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they have become accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
Yet they must wait as voters before they feel the results of the election they have cast their votes in.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy needs time not only for elections, but also for discussions and careful consideration.
However, the consumer as a voter does not accept this and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. However, each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
"Direct action" through demonstrations has become a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of expressing their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet chat pages to electronic messages sent to political leaders.
Then there are also non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic internal structures, but they seem to be still more closely connected to the citizens.
In addition, there is of course the possibility of completely switching off and leaving politics to the experts, so that one can focus on other aspects of life.
The latter probably entails the greatest risks, because it promotes creeping authoritarianism, which is a sign of our time.
But other signs of the separation between politics and citizens also create a rather uncertain situation, because no one can anymore say how representative the prevailing opinions are.
Some would like to break through the knot by means of more direct democracy.
But a continuous connection between leaders and followers cannot be established by reducing public deliberation to simple voting alternatives.
There is much more to be said in favor of maintaining the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and striving to bring them closer again to the citizens.
After all, unpopular parties and declining voter turnout could turn out to be a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and elections and representative governments might once again come to life.
Yet this is probably not sufficient to restore the general legitimacy that the elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the first concern of all those who care deeply about the constitution of freedom must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
